The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Wednesday, July 28, 2004 				 Bengal on hi-tech investment expressway
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Calcutta, July 27: Still trying to break into the league of hi-tech Bangalore and Hyderabad, Bengal has mopped up investment worth Rs 2,500 crore in the twin sectors of IT and telecom in three years.																								We have received investment worth Rs 2,000 crore in telecom and Rs 500 crore in IT and IT-enabled services since 2001-2002, information technology minister Manab Mukherjee said. In his budget speech in the Assembly, the minister described the growth as phenomenal.																								The government hopes to earn 10 per cent of the countrys revenue from the infotech sector by 2006-07. By 2010, we hope to earn 15 per cent of the countrys revenue from the IT sector, Mukherjee said.																								Efforts are on to get IT giant Infosys to invest in the state. Mukherjee pointed out that big players like IBM, Tata Consultancy Services (TCS), Cognizant Technology Solutions and ITC Infotech are here already. 																								Talks are on with other IT companies who want centres in the state. Wipro is about to begin operations and Spectramind, a renowned IT-enabled services company, is ready to invest, he said outside the House.																								Earlier, replying to the discussion on the IT budget, the minister said 10 lakh students in 2,500 schools and madarsas will be brought under the computer literacy programme. We have also decided to bring down the fee to study computers in school to Rs 30 per month.
